{
  "doc_id": "3394",
  "text": "Prior to the results of the RV144 trial, the majority of functional Fc-mediated antibody research focused upon ADCC responses through assays that detected the lysis of target cells or inhibition of viral replication [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Many of the assays were highly complex, difficult to standardize, and time consuming, requiring the use of radioactive cells such as the chromium release assay or virus-infected primary target cells [CITATION_3] . However in the past decade, several high throughput ADCC and other functional Fc-mediated assays have been developed, allowing us to probe multiple other non-neutralizing antibody functions (Table 2 ). These include, but are not limited to, antibody dependent complement dependent cytotoxicity (ADCDC) [CITATION_4] , antibody dependent cellular (or viral) phagocytosis (ADCP) [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , antibody mediated effector cell cytokine and chemokine secretion [CITATION_7] along with antibody dependent cellular viral inhibition (ADCVI) [CITATION_8] . Antibodies also have the capacity to induce multiple other effector functions including, but not limited to antibody dependent enzymatic release/respiratory burst [CITATION_9] and antibody mediated mucus trapping [CITATION_10] ; however, high throughput qualitative robust assays to assess these functions in HIV are still in development.",
